value.value: A shape that inheres in a 3 dimensional entity.
An elasticity which is relatively high.
An elasticity which is relatively low.
A cylindrical shape that is hollow.
A quality that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.
A quality that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.
A quality of an object that has a value that is decreased compared to normal or average.
A quality of an object that has a value that is increased compared to normal or average.

A convex 3-D shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting a by virtue of the bearer's exhibiting a consistently sized and approximately round cross-section along its length, which is many times larger than its diameter.

definition.value: Note that a fiber shaped object may take any circuitous or straight path through space (think of a length of string or rope).

value.value: A shape constituting a transition between a rectangle and a circle; a closed curve, of which the circle and ellipse are special cases, whose parametric equation is x = a.cos2/rt, y = b.cos2/rt
A quality that inheres in a bearer in virtue of its realizing one of its functions.
A quality of an physical object that is currently realizing one of its functions.
An affinity inhering in an anatomical structure by virtue of the bearer exhibiting a molecular interaction for acidic dyes under specific pH conditions.

definition.value: Eosin stains acidophilic structures, hence eosinophilic is the same as acidophilic.

value.value: Having both hydrophilic and hydrophobic (or lipophilic) groups.
Pertaining to the individual parts making up an aggregate fruit like a many-lobed "berry," such as a raspberry.
A composition quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being composed of or possessing inorganic material.
A composition quality inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's consisting of collagen.
A structure quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being capable of swelling or stretching.
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being marked by narrow lines or grooves, usually parallel, that are oriented transversely relative to the long axis of the bearer.
A shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's being marked by narrow lines or grooves, usually parallel, that are oriented obliquely relative to the long axis of the bearer.
A nucleate quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having one or more nucleus.
A surface feature shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's not having undulating edges forming lobes.
A composition quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's consisting of keratin.
A structural quality inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer consisting of multiple structures lacking any physical connection to each other.
A quality of a single cell inhering in the bearer by virtue of the bearer's size or shape or structure.

definition.value: Use this term for morphologies that can *only* inhere in a cell, e.g. morphological qualities inhering in a cell by virtue of the presence, location or shape of one or more cell parts.

value.value: A cellular quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's having multiple cilia.
A quality inhering in a structure by virtue of it consisting of many of repeated, similar or identical subunits, arranged in some orderly array.

definition.value: A complete coverage of this domain would subclasses homopolymeric, copolymeric, crystalline.

value.value: A quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the extent to which the bearer is capable of being stretched or swollen.
A quality inhering in a cell by virtue of the cell having a high nuclear/cytoplasmic ratio.

definition.value: A high nuclear/cytolasmic ratio is 70% or higher.

value.value: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have a small round soma, a large number of short, smooth, or slightly beaded primary dendrites that give rise to only a few secondary branches, and a branched axon that establishes a dense axonal mesh with thin shafts.
A cell morphology that inheres in multipolar neurons with densely branched terminal axonal arborizations that form basket-like structures surrounding and synapsing to the somas of target cells.
A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons with axonal arbors composed of frequent, short, curvy axonal branches that tend to be near their somata and within the same layer.

A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons that are large, and typically ascend to give rise to many long horizontally and vertically projecting axon collaterals that traverse neighboring columns and can extend through all cortical layers.

A basket cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have simpler dendritic arbors (compared to small or large basket cell morphology), and an axonal plexus of intermediate density, composed of a few long, smooth axonal branches.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have two principal dendrites that emerge from the soma and begin to branch some distance from it, have few spines, and branch in narrow fields. This is in contrast to bitufted morphology where branching occurs close to the soma.

definition.value: This is specific to cortical bipolar cells and are distinguished from retinal bipolar cell morphology which has an axon and dendrite emerging from opposite ends of the soma.

value.value: A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which are large and non-spiny, with dendrites radiating in a multipolar or bitufted pattern, often favouring the descending side, and axons that ascend directly from the superficial side of the soma, and travel upward without branching.
A Martinotti cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have axons that form a horizontal ramification, making it T-shaped.
A Martinotti cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have axons that form a fan-like plexus.
A cell morphology that inheres in neurons that have dendritic processes radiating from the cell body forming a star-like shape.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which are small and round, and make highly specialized synapses with the axon initial segments of pyramidal neurons, wrapping them with candle-shaped synaptic 'cartridges'.
Chandelier cells can be bitufted or multipolar.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have two clusters of primary dendrites that originate directly and extend from opposite ends of the soma, and axons that form a plexus which spreads widely. Compared to the narrow vertical axonal projection of bipolar morphology, and the 'horse-tail' axonal cluster of double boquet cells, bitufted morphology has wide horizontal axonal spans, and branching that occur close to the soma. Their vertical projection is also less extensive and crosses mostly to neighboring layers.

A cell morphology that inheres in neurons which have spiny basal dendrites and resemble pyramidal cells but lose their apical dendrites as they mature. Their axons nearly always emerge from the descending side of the soma, but often recurve and ascend with arc-like collaterals.
